  "output": "## Test coverage analysis — jobsquare\n\n**Current state: 0% coverage.** No test files, no test framework in `requirements.txt` (only `httpx`, `PyYAML`), no CI test step (`.github/` has no test workflow visible). Every module below is completely untested. This is a from-scratch gap analysis across the 8 Python modules (~1,500 LOC).\n\n### Recommended test infrastructure (add once, before writing tests)\n\n```\nrequirements-dev.txt:\n  pytest>=8.0\n  pytest-asyncio>=0.24     # fetchers.py and pipeline.py are async\n  respx>=0.21              # httpx mock transport, cleaner than hand-rolled MockTransport\n```\n\n```python\n# conftest.py\nimport pytest\nfrom models import Job\n\n@pytest.fixture\ndef make_job():\n    def _make(**over):\n        base = dict(source=\"greenhouse\", company=\"acme\", external_id=\"1\",\n                    title=\"Engineer\", url=\"https://x/1\", location=\"Remote\")\n        base.update(over)\n        return Job(**base)\n    return _make\n```\n\n---\n\n### 1. `models.py` — Job / parse_posted_at\n\nUntested: `parse_posted_at`, `Job.key`, `Job.posted_dt`, `Job.content_hash`, `Job.to_row`.\n\nKey gaps:\n- No test proves `content_hash` is **insensitive to `salary_range` and `posted_at`** — meaning a comp change alone will never be detected as a \"changed\" job by `Store.diff`. That's a real behavioral edge case worth locking down explicitly (whether intentional or not).\n- Workday's `posted_at` (\"Posted 3 Days Ago\") is prose the docstring calls out, but `parse_posted_at` has no prose-parsing branch — it silently returns `None`. Nothing currently pins this down, so a future refactor could \"fix\" it and change filtering behavior for every Workday source without anyone noticing.\n\n```python\nimport pytest\nfrom datetime import datetime, timezone\nfrom models import Job, parse_posted_at\n\nclass TestParsePostedAt:\n    def test_empty_returns_none(self):\n        assert parse_posted_at(\"\") is None\n\n    def test_epoch_milliseconds(self):\n        dt = parse_posted_at(\"1643241332430\")\n        assert dt == datetime.fromtimestamp(1643241332.430, tz=timezone.utc)\n\n    def test_epoch_seconds(self):\n        dt = parse_posted_at(\"1643241332\")\n        assert dt.tzinfo is not None\n\n    def test_iso_with_z(self):\n        assert parse_posted_at(\"2024-01-01T00:00:00Z\").tzinfo == timezone.utc\n\n    def test_iso_naive_gets_utc_attached(self):\n        assert parse_posted_at(\"2024-01-01T00:00:00\").tzinfo == timezone.utc\n\n    def test_workday_prose_is_unparseable(self):\n        # documents current (intentional?) behavior: filters.match() treats\n        # this as \"keep, can't confirm age\" rather than crashing\n        assert parse_posted_at(\"Posted 3 Days Ago\") is None\n\n    def test_garbage_returns_none(self):\n        assert parse_posted_at(\"not-a-date\") is None\n\n\nclass TestJob:\n    def test_key_stable_across_title_change(self, make_job):\n        j1 = make_job(title=\"Engineer I\")\n        j2 = make_job(title=\"Engineer II\")\n        assert j1.key == j2.key\n\n    def test_content_hash_changes_on_title(self, make_job):\n        assert make_job(title=\"A\").content_hash != make_job(title=\"B\").content_hash\n\n    def test_content_hash_ignores_salary_and_posted_at(self, make_job):\n        j1 = make_job(salary_range=\"100k\", posted_at=\"2024-01-01\")\n        j2 = make_job(salary_range=\"200k\", posted_at=\"2025-01-01\")\n        assert j1.content_hash == j2.content_hash  # documents the gap above\n\n    def test_to_row_strips_raw_adds_key_and_hash(self, make_job):\n        row = make_job(raw={\"secret\": 1}).to_row()\n        assert \"raw\" not in row\n        assert \"key\" in row and \"content_hash\" in row\n```\n\n---\n\n### 2. `store.py` — Store (SQLite dedup)\n\nUntested entirely, including the migration path. Highest-value module to cover since it's the persistence source of truth.\n\n```python\nimport pytest\nfrom store import Store\n\n@pytest.fixture\ndef store(tmp_path):\n    with Store(tmp_path / \"test.db\") as s:\n        yield s\n\nclass TestDiff:\n    def test_new_job_returned_as_new(self, store, make_job):\n        new, changed = store.diff([make_job()])\n        assert len(new) == 1 and changed == []\n\n    def test_unchanged_job_not_returned_either_list(self, store, make_job):\n        j = make_job()\n        store.diff([j])\n        new, changed = store.diff([j])\n        assert new == [] and changed == []\n\n    def test_changed_content_returns_in_changed(self, store, make_job):\n        store.diff([make_job(title=\"Old\")])\n        new, changed = store.diff([make_job(title=\"New\")])\n        assert new == [] and len(changed) == 1\n\n    def test_duplicate_keys_within_same_batch(self, store, make_job):\n        # two Job objects sharing a key in one diff() call — second one\n        # queries after the first's INSERT within the same call\n        j1, j2 = make_job(title=\"A\"), make_job(title=\"B\")\n        new, changed = store.diff([j1, j2])\n        assert len(new) == 1 and len(changed) == 1  # documents actual behavior\n\n    def test_empty_list(self, store):\n        assert store.diff([]) == ([], [])\n\n\nclass TestMigration:\n    def test_adds_salary_range_column_to_legacy_db(self, tmp_path):\n        import sqlite3\n        path = tmp_path / \"legacy.db\"\n        conn = sqlite3.connect(path)\n        conn.execute(\"\"\"CREATE TABLE jobs (key TEXT PRIMARY KEY, source TEXT,\n            company TEXT, external_id TEXT, title TEXT, url TEXT, location TEXT,\n            department TEXT, employment_type TEXT, posted_at TEXT,\n            content_hash TEXT, first_seen TEXT, last_seen TEXT)\"\"\")\n        conn.commit(); conn.close()\n        with Store(path) as s:\n            cols = {r[\"name\"] for r in s.conn.execute(\"PRAGMA table_info(jobs)\")}\n        assert \"salary_range\" in cols\n\n\nclass TestMeta:\n    def test_get_meta_missing_returns_none(self, store):\n        assert store.get_meta(\"last_scan\") is None\n\n    def test_set_then_get_meta(self, store):\n        store.set_meta(\"last_scan\", \"2024-01-01T00:00:00+00:00\")\n        assert store.get_meta(\"last_scan\") == \"2024-01-01T00:00:00+00:00\"\n\n    def test_set_meta_upserts(self, store):\n        store.set_meta(\"k\", \"v1\")\n        store.set_meta(\"k\", \"v2\")\n        assert store.get_meta(\"k\") == \"v2\"\n\n\nclass TestAddedSince:\n    def test_strictly_after_ts_excludes_boundary(self, store, make_job):\n        store.diff([make_job()])\n        row = store.conn.execute(\"SELECT first_seen FROM jobs\").fetchone()\n        assert store.added_since(row[\"first_seen\"]) == []  # boundary excluded\n\n    def test_ordered_by_first_seen_company_title(self, store, make_job):\n        # insert jobs with distinct external_ids, assert ordering\n        ...\n\n    def test_count(self, store, make_job):\n        store.diff([make_job(external_id=\"1\"), make_job(external_id=\"2\")])\n        assert store.count() == 2\n```\n\n---\n\n### 3. `filters.py` — match / filter_jobs\n\nUntested entirely. Key edge cases: word-boundary regex behavior, `None` vs `[]` for optional filter lists, and the \"keep unparseable dates\" rule.\n\n```python\nfrom datetime import datetime, timedelta, timezone\nfrom filters import match, filter_jobs\nfrom models import Job\n\nclass TestMatch:\n    def test_no_filters_passes(self, make_job):\n        assert match(make_job()) is True\n\n    def test_exclude_blocks(self, make_job):\n        assert match(make_job(title=\"Senior Recruiter\"), exclude=[\"recruiter\"]) is False\n\n    def test_include_word_boundary_java_does_not_match_javascript(self, make_job):\n        assert match(make_job(title=\"JavaScript Engineer\"), include=[\"java\"]) is False\n\n    def test_include_none_means_no_filter(self, make_job):\n        assert match(make_job(title=\"anything\"), include=None) is True\n\n    def test_locations_empty_list_is_no_filter(self, make_job):\n        assert match(make_job(location=\"\"), locations=[]) is True\n\n    def test_locations_no_match_excludes(self, make_job):\n        assert match(make_job(location=\"Berlin\"), locations=[\"NYC\"]) is False\n\n    def test_cutoff_keeps_unparseable_posted_at(self, make_job):\n        j = make_job(posted_at=\"Posted 3 Days Ago\")  # Workday prose, unparseable\n        assert match(j, cutoff=datetime.now(timezone.utc)) is True\n\n    def test_cutoff_excludes_older_job(self, make_job):\n        old = (datetime.now(timezone.utc) - timedelta(days=30)).isoformat()\n        j = make_job(posted_at=old)\n        assert match(j, cutoff=datetime.now(timezone.utc) - timedelta(days=1)) is False\n\n    def test_cutoff_keeps_newer_job(self, make_job):\n        j = make_job(posted_at=datetime.now(timezone.utc).isoformat())\n        assert match(j, cutoff=datetime.now(timezone.utc) - timedelta(days=1)) is True\n\n\nclass TestFilterJobs:\n    def test_max_age_days_computes_cutoff(self, make_job):\n        old = (datetime.now(timezone.utc) - timedelta(days=10)).isoformat()\n        jobs = [make_job(posted_at=old)]\n        assert filter_jobs(jobs, {\"max_age_days\": 5}) == []\n\n    def test_empty_rules_dict_passes_everything(self, make_job):\n        assert filter_jobs([make_job()], {}) == [make_job()]\n```\n\n---\n\n### 4. `pipeline.py` — load_config / run / run_sync\n\nUntested entirely — this is the orchestration glue, worth an integration-style test with everything mocked.\n\n```python\nimport pytest\nfrom unittest.mock import AsyncMock, patch\nfrom pipeline import load_config, run\n\nclass TestLoadConfig:\n    def test_defaults_applied(self, tmp_path):\n        p = tmp_path / \"c.yaml\"\n        p.write_text(\"sources: []\")\n        cfg = load_config(p)\n        assert cfg[\"filters\"] == {} and cfg[\"db\"] == \"jobs.db\" and cfg[\"concurrency\"] == 8\n\n    def test_explicit_values_not_overridden(self, tmp_path):\n        p = tmp_path / \"c.yaml\"\n        p.write_text(\"sources: []\\nconcurrency: 2\\ndb: other.db\")\n        cfg = load_config(p)\n        assert cfg[\"concurrency\"] == 2 and cfg[\"db\"] == \"other.db\"\n\n\nclass TestRun:\n    @pytest.mark.asyncio\n    async def test_dry_run_does_not_touch_store_or_notify(self, tmp_path, make_job):\n        cfg_path = tmp_path / \"c.yaml\"\n        cfg_path.write_text(f\"sources: []\\ndb: {tmp_path/'x.db'}\")\n        with patch(\"pipeline.fetch_all\", AsyncMock(return_value=[make_job()])), \\\n             patch(\"pipeline.dispatch\") as mock_dispatch:\n            result = await run(cfg_path, dry_run=True)\n        mock_dispatch.assert_not_called()\n        assert result == {\"matched\": 1, \"new\": 0, \"changed\": 0}\n\n    @pytest.mark.asyncio\n    async def test_full_run_persists_and_notifies(self, tmp_path, make_job):\n        cfg_path = tmp_path / \"c.yaml\"\n        cfg_path.write_text(f\"sources: []\\ndb: {tmp_path/'x.db'}\")\n        with patch(\"pipeline.fetch_all\", AsyncMock(return_value=[make_job()])), \\\n             patch(\"pipeline.dispatch\") as mock_dispatch:\n            result = await run(cfg_path, dry_run=False)\n        mock_dispatch.assert_called_once()\n        assert result[\"new\"] == 1\n```\n\n---\n\n### 5. `notify.py` — dispatch and per-channel notifiers\n\nUntested entirely, including the error-isolation guarantee in `dispatch` — this is the single most important behavior in this module (one broken webhook shouldn't kill SMS/email) and nothing currently proves it.\n\n```python\nimport pytest\nfrom unittest.mock import patch, Mock\nfrom notify import dispatch, notify_slack, notify_sms, _sms_body, notify_email\n\nclass TestDispatch:\n    def test_one_notifier_failing_does_not_block_others(self, make_job):\n        calls = []\n        def boom(new, changed): raise RuntimeError(\"webhook down\")\n        def ok(new, changed): calls.append(\"ran\")\n        with patch(\"notify.NOTIFIERS\", [boom, ok]):\n            dispatch([make_job()], [])\n        assert calls == [\"ran\"]\n\n\nclass TestNotifySlack:\n    def test_noop_without_env_var(self, monkeypatch, make_job):\n        monkeypatch.delenv(\"SLACK_WEBHOOK_URL\", raising=False)\n        with patch(\"notify.httpx.post\") as post:\n            notify_slack([make_job()], [])\n        post.assert_not_called()\n\n    def test_noop_when_nothing_new_or_changed(self, monkeypatch):\n        monkeypatch.setenv(\"SLACK_WEBHOOK_URL\", \"https://hooks/x\")\n        with patch(\"notify.httpx.post\") as post:\n            notify_slack([], [])\n        post.assert_not_called()\n\n    def test_posts_when_configured_and_new(self, monkeypatch, make_job):\n        monkeypatch.setenv(\"SLACK_WEBHOOK_URL\", \"https://hooks/x\")\n        with patch(\"notify.httpx.post\") as post:\n            notify_slack([make_job()], [])\n        post.assert_called_once()\n\n\nclass TestSmsBody:\n    def test_truncates_after_limit_with_more_count(self, make_job):\n        jobs = [make_job(external_id=str(i), title=f\"Role {i}\") for i in range(10)]\n        body = _sms_body(jobs, [], limit=8)\n        assert \"+2 more\" in body\n\n    def test_ascii_only_no_bullets_or_ellipsis(self, make_job):\n        body = _sms_body([make_job()], [])\n        assert \"\\u2022\" not in body and \"\\u2026\" not in body\n\n\nclass TestNotifySms:\n    def test_missing_any_of_four_env_vars_noops(self, monkeypatch, make_job):\n        monkeypatch.setenv(\"TWILIO_ACCOUNT_SID\", \"sid\")\n        # TWILIO_AUTH_TOKEN intentionally unset\n        with patch(\"notify.httpx.post\") as post:\n            notify_sms([make_job()], [])\n        post.assert_not_called()\n\n    def test_bad_response_raises_via_raise_for_status(self, monkeypatch, make_job):\n        for k, v in [(\"TWILIO_ACCOUNT_SID\",\"s\"),(\"TWILIO_AUTH_TOKEN\",\"t\"),\n                     (\"TWILIO_FROM\",\"+1\"),(\"TWILIO_TO\",\"+2\")]:\n            monkeypatch.setenv(k, v)\n        resp = Mock(); resp.raise_for_status.side_effect = RuntimeError(\"401\")\n        with patch(\"notify.httpx.post\", return_value=resp):\n            with pytest.raises(RuntimeError):\n                notify_sms([make_job()], [])\n```\n\nAlso missing: `notify_email` SMTP happy path + `SMTP_USER` login branch (needs `smtplib.SMTP` mocked), and `notify_webhook` payload shape (`{\"new\": [...], \"changed\": [...]}` using `to_row()`).\n\n---\n\n### 6. `fetchers.py` — largest untested surface (787 lines, ~30 functions)\n\nThis is the highest-risk module because every `parse_*` function encodes undocumented, brittle assumptions about third-party JSON/HTML shapes. Group by pattern rather than writing 15 near-identical blocks:\n\n**A. Retry/transport layer (`_request`) — test in isolation with `respx` or a hand-rolled `httpx.MockTransport`:**\n\n```python\nimport httpx, pytest\nfrom fetchers import _request\n\n@pytest.mark.asyncio\nasync def test_retries_on_retryable_status_then_succeeds(monkeypatch):\n    monkeypatch.setattr(\"fetchers.asyncio.sleep\", AsyncMock())  # skip real backoff\n    calls = {\"n\": 0}\n    def handler(request):\n        calls[\"n\"] += 1\n        if calls[\"n\"] < 3:\n            return httpx.Response(503)\n        return httpx.Response(200, json={\"ok\": True})\n    async with httpx.AsyncClient(transport=httpx.MockTransport(handler)) as client:\n        r = await _request(client, \"https://x\")\n    assert r.status_code == 200 and calls[\"n\"] == 3\n\n@pytest.mark.asyncio\nasync def test_exhausts_retries_raises_runtime_error(monkeypatch):\n    monkeypatch.setattr(\"fetchers.asyncio.sleep\", AsyncMock())\n    async def always_503(request): return httpx.Response(503)\n    async with httpx.AsyncClient(transport=httpx.MockTransport(always_503)) as client:\n        with pytest.raises(RuntimeError):\n            await _request(client, \"https://x\", retries=2)\n\n@pytest.mark.asyncio\nasync def test_non_retryable_404_still_gets_retried_before_failing(monkeypatch):\n    # documents a real inefficiency: raise_for_status() raises HTTPStatusError\n    # for ANY 4xx, which the except clause catches and retries needlessly\n    monkeypatch.setattr(\"fetchers.asyncio.sleep\", AsyncMock())\n    calls = {\"n\": 0}\n    def handler(request):\n        calls[\"n\"] += 1\n        return httpx.Response(404)\n    async with httpx.AsyncClient(transport=httpx.MockTransport(handler)) as client:\n        with pytest.raises(RuntimeError):\n            await _request(client, \"https://x\", retries=3)\n    assert calls[\"n\"] == 3  # wasted retries on a permanent error\n```\n\n**B. Parser normalization functions — pure functions, no network, cheapest to test.** For each of `parse_greenhouse`, `parse_lever`, `parse_ashby`, `parse_smartrecruiters`, `parse_recruitee`, `parse_workable`, `parse_google`, `parse_deshaw`, `parse_twosigma`, `parse_optiver`, `parse_meta`, `parse_microsoft`, `parse_netflix`, `parse_amazon`, apply this shared skeleton shape (only `parse_lever` shown fully; repeat per-source with that source's own defensive-default fields):\n\n```python\nfrom fetchers import parse_lever, _lever_salary\n\nclass TestParseLever:\n    def test_normal_payload(self):\n        data = [{\"id\": \"1\", \"text\": \"Engineer\", \"hostedUrl\": \"https://x\",\n                 \"categories\": {\"location\": \"NYC\", \"team\": \"Eng\", \"commitment\": \"FT\"},\n                 \"createdAt\": 1700000000000}]\n        jobs = parse_lever(\"acme\", data)\n        assert jobs[0].location == \"NYC\" and jobs[0].employment_type == \"FT\"\n\n    def test_missing_categories_defaults_empty(self):\n        jobs = parse_lever(\"acme\", [{\"id\": \"1\", \"text\": \"E\", \"hostedUrl\": \"u\"}])\n        assert jobs[0].location == \"\" and jobs[0].department == \"\"\n\nclass TestLeverSalary:\n    def test_min_max_formats_with_commas(self):\n        assert _lever_salary({\"salaryRange\": {\"min\": 100000, \"max\": 150000, \"currency\": \"USD\"}}) \\\n            == \"USD 100,000–150,000\"\n\n    def test_falls_back_to_plain_description(self):\n        assert _lever_salary({\"salaryDescriptionPlain\": \"Competitive\"}) == \"Competitive\"\n\n    def test_neither_present_returns_empty(self):\n        assert _lever_salary({}) == \"\"\n```\n\nHighest-value edge cases per remaining parser (currently zero coverage on any of these):\n- `parse_ashby`: `isListed is False` jobs must be filtered out; `id` vs `jobId` fallback.\n- `parse_google` / `_extract_ds1`: primary regex miss falling through to the fallback regex; invalid embedded JSON returning `[]`; `job[0]` falsy entries skipped; out-of-range index access on short arrays.\n- `_ds1_posted_at`: preference order index 12 → 13 → 14; all absent → `\"\"`.\n- `parse_deshaw` / `parse_twosigma`: dedup of repeated cards/anchors (both explicitly documented as rendering the same job 2–3x); location lookup window bounded to the next anchor.\n- `_amazon_posted_at`: valid `\"June 26, 2026\"` string; malformed string and unknown month name both degrading to `\"\"` via caught `ValueError`/`KeyError` (currently no test proves the except clause is reachable at all).\n- `parse_meta`: dedup by id; blank id skipped; token-scraping regexes (`lsd`, `__spin_r`, `__spin_b`, `__spin_t`) with `\"for (;;);\"` XSSI prefix stripped before JSON parse; `data[\"errors\"]` triggers `RuntimeError` (simulates a rotated `doc_id`, the failure mode the module docstring explicitly warns about).\n\n**C. Pagination fetchers (`fetch_workday`, `fetch_google`, `fetch_meta`, `fetch_microsoft`, `fetch_netflix`, `fetch_amazon`, `fetch_twosigma`, `fetch_optiver`) — need `httpx.MockTransport` sequencing multiple responses:**\n\n```python\n@pytest.mark.asyncio\nasync def test_fetch_workday_stops_at_total_and_respects_5000_cap(monkeypatch):\n    def handler(request):\n        return httpx.Response(200, json={\"jobPostings\": [{\"title\": \"E\",\n            \"externalPath\": \"/job/1\", \"bulletFields\": [\"R1\"]}], \"total\": 1})\n    async with httpx.AsyncClient(transport=httpx.MockTransport(handler)) as client:\n        jobs = await fetch_workday(client, {\"host\": \"h\", \"tenant\": \"t\", \"site\": \"s\"})\n    assert len(jobs) == 1  # loop must stop once offset >= total, not loop forever\n```\n\nApply the same \"stop on no-fresh-page\" + \"respect max_pages\" pattern to each of the other seven pagination fetchers — none currently prove the pagination loop actually terminates, which matters given several have safety caps in the dozens of pages.\n\n**D. Registry / dispatch:**\n\n```python\nfrom fetchers import fetch_source, fetch_all\nimport pytest\n\n@pytest.mark.asyncio\nasync def test_fetch_source_unknown_ats_raises_valueerror():\n    with pytest.raises(ValueError, match=\"unknown ATS\"):\n        await fetch_source(None, {\"ats\": \"bogus\"})\n\n@pytest.mark.asyncio\nasync def test_fetch_all_one_source_failing_does_not_abort_others(monkeypatch):\n    async def fake_fetch_source(client, src):\n        if src[\"ats\"] == \"boom\": raise RuntimeError(\"down\")\n        return [Job(source=\"x\", company=\"c\", external_id=\"1\", title=\"t\", url=\"u\")]\n    monkeypatch.setattr(\"fetchers.fetch_source\", fake_fetch_source)\n    jobs = await fetch_all([{\"ats\": \"boom\", \"company\": \"b\"}, {\"ats\": \"ok\", \"company\": \"c\"}])\n    assert len(jobs) == 1\n\n@pytest.mark.asyncio\nasync def test_fetch_all_reuses_injected_client_without_closing_it():\n    client = httpx.AsyncClient()\n    await fetch_all([], client=client)\n    assert not client.is_closed\n    await client.aclose()\n```\n\n---\n\n### 7. `agent.py` — CLI + deterministic helpers + PDF rendering\n\nUntested entirely.\n\n```python\nfrom agent import cmd_db_new, cmd_db_mark, _normalize_ats\nimport json\n\nclass TestDbNew:\n    def test_first_run_uses_since_days_window(self, tmp_path, capsys, make_job):\n        cfg = tmp_path / \"c.yaml\"; cfg.write_text(f\"db: {tmp_path/'j.db'}\\nsources: []\")\n        with Store(tmp_path / \"j.db\") as s:\n            s.diff([make_job()])\n        cmd_db_new([\"-c\", str(cfg), \"--since-days\", \"7\"])\n        out = json.loads(capsys.readouterr().out)\n        assert out[\"first_run\"] is True and out[\"count\"] == 1\n\n    def test_truncates_at_group_boundary_not_mid_group(self, tmp_path, capsys, make_job):\n        # rows sharing one first_seen timestamp must never be split by --limit\n        ...\n\nclass TestDbMark:\n    def test_invalid_watermark_returns_2(self, tmp_path, capsys):\n        cfg = tmp_path / \"c.yaml\"; cfg.write_text(f\"db: {tmp_path/'j.db'}\\nsources: []\")\n        assert cmd_db_mark([\"not-a-date\", \"-c\", str(cfg)]) == 2\n\n    def test_neither_watermark_nor_now_returns_2(self, tmp_path):\n        cfg = tmp_path / \"c.yaml\"; cfg.write_text(f\"db: {tmp_path/'j.db'}\\nsources: []\")\n        assert cmd_db_mark([\"-c\", str(cfg)]) == 2\n\n\nclass TestNormalizeAts:\n    def test_replaces_smart_quotes_in_body(self):\n        html, counts = _normalize_ats(\"<p>\\u201cHello\\u201d</p>\")\n        assert '\"Hello\"' in html and counts[\"smart-double-quote\"] == 1\n\n    def test_does_not_touch_style_or_script_blocks(self):\n        html, counts = _normalize_ats(\"<style>content: '\\u2014';</style><p>a\\u2014b</p>\")\n        assert \"\\u2014\" in html  # inside <style>, untouched\n        assert counts[\"em-dash\"] == 1  # only the <p> occurrence counted\n\n    def test_does_not_touch_tag_attributes(self):\n        html, _ = _normalize_ats('<a title=\"x\\u2014y\">a\\u2014b</a>')\n        assert 'title=\"x\\u2014y\"' in html  # attribute preserved\n```\n\nAlso missing: `cmd_pdf_render` (missing-input-file → return 2; `%PDF` magic-byte failure path → return 1; CSS injected before `</head>` vs. prepended when no `<head>` exists — needs `subprocess.run` mocked, no real Chrome dependency), `_chrome_bin` (CHROME_PATH env precedence → `shutil.which` → hardcoded app paths → `sys.exit`), and `main()`'s argv-splitting logic (mode words vs. passthrough flags, `-i`/`--interactive` detection).\n\n---\n\n### 8. `cli.py`\n\nTrivial but untested:\n\n```python\nfrom unittest.mock import patch\nfrom cli import main\n\ndef test_main_passes_dry_run_and_config(monkeypatch):\n    monkeypatch.setattr(\"sys.argv\", [\"cli.py\", \"-c\", \"custom.yaml\", \"--dry-run\"])\n    with patch(\"cli.run_sync\") as run_sync:\n        main()\n    run_sync.assert_called_once_with(\"custom.yaml\", dry_run=True)\n```\n\n---\n\n### Integration test gaps\n\nNo test currently exercises more than one module together. Worth one end-to-end test:\n\n```python\n@pytest.mark.asyncio\nasync def test_pipeline_end_to_end_greenhouse_to_store(tmp_path, monkeypatch):\n    \"\"\"fetch (mocked HTTP) -> filter -> store.diff -> dispatch, real SQLite.\"\"\"\n    cfg = tmp_path / \"c.yaml\"\n    cfg.write_text(f\"\"\"\nsources: [{{ats: greenhouse, company: acme}}]\nfilters: {{include_keywords: [engineer]}}\ndb: {tmp_path / 'jobs.db'}\n\"\"\")\n    def handler(request):\n        return httpx.Response(200, json={\"jobs\": [\n            {\"id\": 1, \"title\": \"Software Engineer\", \"absolute_url\": \"https://x/1\"}]})\n    monkeypatch.setattr(\"fetchers.httpx.AsyncClient\",\n        lambda **kw: httpx.AsyncClient(transport=httpx.MockTransport(handler), **kw))\n    result = await run(cfg, dry_run=False)\n    assert result == {\"matched\": 1, \"new\": 1, \"changed\": 0}\n    # run again: same job should now be neither new nor changed\n    result2 = await run(cfg, dry_run=False)\n    assert result2 == {\"matched\": 1, \"new\": 0, \"changed\": 0}\n```\n\nAlso worth one for `agent.py`'s `db-new`/`db-mark` cycle against a real pipeline run (scan marker only advances on explicit `db-mark`, never on `db-new` — this invariant is the crux of the scan workflow and is currently unverified).\n\n---\n\n### Priority if coverage work is scoped incrementally\n\n1. `filters.py` + `models.py` — pure functions, cheap, high logic density (dedup/hash/date parsing bugs are silent and compound over time).\n2. `store.py` — SQLite dedup is the source of truth; a bug here means duplicate or lost notifications.\n3. `notify.py` `dispatch()` error isolation — one flaky webhook shouldn't silently kill Twilio/email.\n4. `fetchers.py` parser functions (pure, no network) — each `parse_*` is a brittle contract with an external API; these break silently when a vendor changes JSON shape, and only tests catch it before a bad prod run.\n5. `fetchers.py` pagination/retry loops — need mocked HTTP, more setup, but termination bugs here mean either infinite loops or silently truncated job lists.\n6. `agent.py` — CLI helpers and PDF rendering, more OS-dependent/harder to unit test cleanly (subprocess/Chrome).\n",
